Fundraising

July 2024 Fundraising Report

Tehsin Amlani

2 days ago   15 min read

Key Insights

  • Fundraising volume increased 72.9% MoM to $1.44 billion despite a 8.3% MoM decrease in deal count to 177.
  • The most notable deals included Sentient ($85 million), ID Planet ($80 million), Partior ($60 million), Ceti ($60 million), and NPC Labs ($18 million).
  • Pantera Capital and Mirana Ventures played a key role in funding, each leading two of the five largest early-stage deals.
  • The Infrastructure Sector saw the most fundraising volume at $760 million, accounting for 52.7% of total fundraising volume.

In July, deal volume increased by 72.9% MoM to $1.44 billion, while the deal count decreased by 8.3% MoM to 177. Three post-IPO projects, all within the Mining Operations and Support sub-sector, significantly contributed to the increase in deal volume.

  • IREN: Raised $413.4 million from selling 39.8 million shares. IREN operates data centers for Bitcoin mining and provides AI cloud services.
  • Alps Blockchain: Secured $113 million in a funding round led by Azimut. Alps Blockchain builds and operates mining farms.
  • Argo Blockchain: Raised $8.3 million from selling 57.8 million shares. Argo blockchain uses clean energy to manage large-scale mining facilities.

Excluding these deals from July's fundraising data, deal volume would have increased by only 8.8% MoM to $908 million.

The infrastructure sector raised the highest amount at $760 million, followed by the financial sector at $241 million, and the consumer Sector at $122 million. However, excluding the above mentioned post-IPO raises in the infrastructure sector, the financial sector would rank first, the infrastructure sector second at $225 million, and the Consumer Sector third. Pantera Capital and Mirana Ventures played a key role in funding, each leading two of the five largest early-stage deals in July.

Infrastructure Sector

Fundraising volume in the infrastructure sector increased by 275% MoM to $760 million, accounting for 52.7% of the total fundraising volume and marking it as the most funded sector. Deal count increased by 24% MoM to 26, representing 14.6% of the total deal count. The significant increase in deal volume was primarily driven by the three post-IPO deals in the Mining Operations and Services sub-sector.

Sentient

Sentient announced a $85 million mega seed round led by Peter Thiels Founders Fund, Pantera Capital, and Framework Ventures. Sentient terms itself as an AI research organization building a community-owned artificial general intelligence. It aims to do this by fostering collaboration among open-source AI developers and helping them monetize their models. Sentient sits at the very exciting intersection of AI and crypto.

The project is led by industry titans Sandeep Nailwal (Polygon), Pramod Vishwanath (Witness Chain), Himanshu Tyagi (Witness Chain), and Kenzi Wang (Symbolic VC). Further it is also supported by Sreeram Kannan (EigenLayer). Unsurprisingly, this strong team was the primary attraction for Sentients high-profile investors.

The Bull Case: Sentient is an early-stage project, so there are few publicly available details. Founders Fund describes Sentient as somewhat similar to Ethereum but for decentralized and open-source AI models instead of decentralized applications. It is trying to overcome the lead of the biggest players in tech, Google, Meta, OpenAI, and X (formerly Twitter), by coordinating grass-roots open-source developers. If it works, it is safe to say that it will be bullish.

The Bear Case: Sentient may have to compete with mega Tech firms and national governments for the highly sought-after AI talent. Unless the incentives are comparable, Sentient will have to work with only open-source missionaries. Further, Sentient is in an early stage of development with no public product. The road to open-source AGI is long.

For more insight into Infrastructure and AI - check out Messaris Dissecting the Intersection of AI and Crypto and The Infrastructure vs Application Debate.

Hash AI

In July, Hash AI raised $10 million in an undisclosed funding round led by Bolts Capital. Hash AI integrates AI and utilizes sustainable energy sources to operate crypto mining infrastructure.

Hash AI is a new entrant in the Mining Operations and Services space. The primary challenge for Hash AI is to sustainably differentiate itself enough from established competitors and maintain competitive differentiation to become a market leader in the crypto mining industry. While some crypto mining companies, such as Applied Digital and BlockQuarry, have integrated AI to repurpose mining infrastructure to provide AI-optimized cloud services or AI-driven data storage, Hash AI is among the first to combine sustainable energy and AI algorithms to optimize mining efficiency and output.

The Bull Case: Miners are essential to the security and stability of many networks. Without industrial-scale mining, the security of these networks would be less secure, thereby underscoring the strong product-market fit of miners. Hash AI separates itself by addressing the immense operational costs and market risks that challenge traditional miners.

Most mining operations rely on fossil fuels or grid-tied power sources, leading to high energy prices and volatility. In contrast, Hash AI uses sustainable energy sources, offering stable and often lower-cost energy after the initial infrastructure investment. This stability reduces operational expenses and insulates Hash AI from price shocks that affect competitors.

Additionally, Hash AI uses custom AI-algorithms to analyze real-time data across multiple networks, adjusting its strategies to mine the most profitable cryptocurrencies. The company utilizes a diverse mix of mining rigs, including GPUs and ASICs, allowing it to mine a wide-range of assets. By leveraging AI and maintaining a more versatile infrastructure than traditional mining operations, Hash AI is better able to minimize downtime and volatile market risks, generating higher profit margins per mined token.

The Bear Case: Several risks could undermine Hash AIs success. First, the initial infrastructure investment required for sustainable energy sources is substantial, and if these costs are not offset by sufficient operational savings and increased profitability, the financial viability of Hash AI would be compromised. Second, the mining landscape is fiercely competitive, with highly capable firms that may deploy similar AI algorithms, reducing Hash AIs profit margins and competitive advantage. Third, Hash AIs AI-integrated mix of mining rigs poses technical and operational challenges given the effectiveness of its AI-driven strategies is critically dependent on the accuracy of data processing and reliability of real-time market data. Any discrepancies or failures in data accuracy can lead to significant misallocation of resources, operational inefficiencies, and exacerbated financial losses.

Mira

Mira raised $9 million in a seed round with investments from Balaji Srinivasan, Framework Ventures, Sandeep Nailwal, Mechanism Capital, Bitkraft Ventures and 13 others. Mira is a decentralized AI infrastructure platform enabling the creation and monetization of AI products.

The Bull Case: The AI x Crypto Infrastructure sector continues to exhibit significant growth, driven by substantial investments with $230 million invested last month alone and increasing demand for addressing data privacy, antitrust issues, censorship, and the monopolistic practices of centralized systems. Mira's game-theoretic ML systems and stake-based model evaluation leverage economic primitives to enhance AI model reliability and performance, capitalizing on the limitations of centralized systems, which heavily depend on monetizing user data. The companys focus on onchain AI resource markets and novel attribution systems streamline developer workflow in creating and maintaining complex AI products in a manner that sets them apart from similar market players such as SingularityNET and Ocean Protocol. With the AI x Crypto Infrastructure sector in its early stages, increasing consumer demand and Miras focus on optimizing AI workflows provide it with an opportunity to capture market share within its niche, where a clear market leader has not yet emerged. If the decentralized AI narrative succeeds, Mira has the potential to become one of the leading AI infrastructure platforms.

The Bear Case: Miras primary competitorscentralized systemsare entrenched, highly scalable, and possess a monopoly on talent, presenting substantial barriers for Mira to overcome. Despite growing demand for decentralized AI alternatives, enterprises and institutions remain risk-averse, still favoring contracts over smart contracts. Further, Mira's reliance on community-driven workflows and decentralized evaluation mechanisms may not achieve the same level of reliability and performance as those of centralized systems. Thus, for Mira to gain meaningful traction, it must match the performance and economic viability of centralized alternatives while minimizing consumer switching costs and concerns. If it fails to do so, it will severely struggle to gain meaningful traction.

Financial Sector

In July, the Financial sector raised $241 million, a 63.7% MoM increase, accounting for 16.7% of the total fundraising volume. Deal count marginally increased by 2.6% MoM to 40, representing 22.5% of the total deal count and the highest deal count of the three most funded sectors. The Financial sector demonstrated the greatest balance in funding across its subsectors and had no funding deals exceeding $100 million.

Partior

Partior raised $60 million in a series B round, with investments from industry titans like J.P. Morgan, Temasek, Peak XV Partners, and Jump Trading. Partior is a cross-border transaction settlement platform for financial institutions. It works with commercial banks, central banks, market infrastructures, and technology partners.

The Bull Case: The projected increase in cross-border payments from $150 trillion in 2017 to $250 trillion by 2027 underscores the growing reliance on traditional wholesale payment systems and correspondent banking networks. These systems incur transaction fees of approximately 0.5%, amounting to about $120 billion, excluding significant foreign exchange (FX) costs. The lack of automation and real-time settlement, due to the complexity of managing multiple operational processes, introduces inefficiencies, costs, delays, and risks. Partior has positioned itself over the past eight years to mitigate these issues by recently launching a 24x7 global atomic clearing and settlement system with real-time and programmable features for commercial bank money (M1) and, in the future, central bank money (M0). As the cross-border transactions market expands, the demand for risk-free, efficient, and reliable settlement solutions becomes increasingly critical, providing Partior the opportunity to become the market leader in cross-border transaction settlements.

The Bear Case: There are three primary considerations that may impede Partiors growth:

  1. Regulatory Barriers - The financial industry is heavily regulated, and new technologies must navigate a complex web of global regulations and red tape. Any delays in obtaining necessary approvals or compliance failures could stall Partiors development and adoption.
  2. Integration - Integrating Partior's system with existing financial infrastructure requires substantial coordination with banks and financial institutions. The process of overhauling or integrating legacy systems can be slow due to the inherent risks and costs involved.
  3. Competition - The cross-border payment space is highly competitive, with established players such as SWIFT, Ripple, and emerging fintech companies continually innovating. Partior must not only demonstrate superior value but also convincingly differentiate itself enough from competitors to win and keep clients.

For more insight into payments - check out Messaris Web3 Payments: Catalyzing Cryptos Next Wave of Application Innovation.

Lombard

Lombard raised $16 million in a seed round with investments from Polychain Capital, Robot Ventures, OKX Ventures, Mirana Ventures, Foresight Ventures, and 9 others. Lombard integrates Bitcoin into DeFi. Their primary service is LBTC, a yield-bearing, cross-chain, liquid Bitcoin, which allows Bitcoin to be used in DeFi to earn, stake, and trade without liquidity fragmentation.

The Bull Case: The conventional view: Bitcoin is primarily a digital store of value, whereas Ethereum and other smart contract-enabled networks are foundations for building onchain applications or providing crucial services such as Data Availability, Consensus, and/or Settlement. However, this is changing as Bitcoin enters into a renaissance of programmability and modularity. Ordinal Theory emphasized the demand for added functionality, and then BitVM brought expressive and trust-minimized L2s within reach. With Bitcoin programmability progressing, the vast majority of EVM smart contract use cases, especially DeFi, the most popular use case, will seek to capitalize on Bitcoins idle capital, network effects, mindshare and vast user base. This places Lombard in a special position to take full advantage.

The Bear Case: While Lombard has the potential to unlock Bitcoins vast DeFi potential, the potential may not be as explosive as it may initially seem. If WBTC is used as a proxy to gauge BTC DeFi demand, the market cap of WBTC, which is $8.5 billion, represents only 0.7% of BTCs $1.1 trillion market cap. BTC holders who seek access to DeFi services can convert BTC to WBTC and use well-established DeFi protocols, such as Aave, rather than untested Bitcoin DeFi products and services. Moreover, exchanges and institutions such as Grayscale heavily favor holding BTC directly to minimize tax obligations, counterparty risk, and smart contract risk. As such, the entrenched narrative of Bitcoin being simply a store of value may severely limit Lombards upside potential.

For more insight into Bitcoin DeFi - check out Messaris Discussion: Does Bitcoin need Layer-2s? and Babylon: Bitcoin Shared Security and Staking.

Consumer Sector

The Consumer sector raised $122.5 million in July, a 179.5% MoM increase, accounting for 8.5% of the total fundraising volume. The deal count decreased by 24% MoM to 16, representing 9% of the total deal count and the lowest deal count of the three most funded sectors in July.

ID Planet

ID Planet raised $80 million in a series B round led by AccelByte and Lam Group. ID Planet is a Web3 metaverse hub utilizing a Layer-1 blockchain, providing services such as decentralized (ID.SWAP) and centralized (IDPLANETXC) exchanges, an NFT marketplace (ID.NFT), a social finance app (ID.FRIEND), and a crypto wallet (IDC20 Wallet).

The Bull Case: Avatar NFTs have evolved to function as expressive representations of online personas, closely linked to their owners' social capital, reputation, and status. While platforms like X (formerly Twitter) offer spaces for social interaction, there are limited venues where users can leverage their digital identities to play games, socialize, and transact NFTs all in one place. ID Planet intends to create such a hub, combining Web3 gaming and social experiences with NFT transaction capabilities. The metaverses promise to offer enhanced gaming experiences to vibrant social communities has long been touted as one of the biggest catalysts for the mass adoption of crypto, bringing in over $4.5 billion in funding over the last two years alone. The metaverse offers value propositions such as full ownership of in-game assets, digital identities, and cross-game interoperability. As interest in the metaverse continues to rise, ID Planet is poised to grow alongside it.

The Bear Case: Despite growing interest in the metaverse over recent years, the sector has yet to significantly disrupt Web3. ID Planet may struggle to attract users beyond the crypto-native community familiar with onchain experiences. Social media platforms typically gain traction when embraced by the younger generation. While ID Planet offers several unique features, it has not yet launched to test its value proposition. Additionally, ID Planet's broad array of potential use cases could be a drawback. Developing and operating diverse infrastructures for different verticals is challenging, and the protocol might fail to achieve significant usage in any single area if it spreads its focus too thin.

For more insight into the Metaverse - check out Messaris Web3s Role in The Metaverse and UGX: User Generated Experiences.

Igloo

Igloo raised $11 million in a strategic round with investments from Fenbushi Capital, 1kx, Founders Fund, Everest Ventures Group (EVG), Selini Capital, and 1 other. Igloo, Inc. is the parent company behind the Pudgy Penguins NFT collection and a Web3 IP platform for crypto brand building.

The Bull Case: Brands often find leveraging intellectual property (IP) attractive because its low risk and requires less effort compared to developing new revenue streams. There is a long history of successful IP utilization, from Pokmon, which has generated $150 billion in lifetime revenue, to the Harry Potter brands video game, Hogwarts Legacy, selling 24 million copies and earning over $1 billion in revenue. Leveraging IP may be one of the best ways to grow crypto-native brands and onboard new users into the space.

A notable example is Pudgy Penguins, which continues to expand beyond the digital sphere by introducing its artwork into tangible mediums such as plush toys, which sold over 1 million units and generated $10 million in sales in its first year of launch. This expansion into plush toys reinvigorated the Pudgy Penguins community, placed the brand on 31,000 Walmart shelves, made it the top seller in several categories on Amazon, and earned it Toy Insiders Top Summer Toy of 2023 award. Brand building, IP, and consulting are significant businesses outside the crypto world, but within crypto, there are few players. Thus, Pudgy Penguins parent company, Igloo, is uniquely positioned to not only be the market leader in crypto branding but also help crypto-native creators build their brand and IP to generate new revenue streams and ignite community engagement.

The Bear Case: Building a brand is inherently difficult, with the majority of new IPs failing to gain traction. Success requires creating work and a narrative that resonates with a large audience, a task that is even more daunting within the crypto space. The Bored Ape Yacht Club (BAYC) NFT collection exemplifies these difficulties.

BAYC had the strongest NFT narrative last cycle, the most active community, endorsements from prominent public figures from both within and outside the crypto space and achieved an all-time high floor price of over $430,000. After launching several successful gamified experiences, they intensified their focus on building their brand in gaming through ventures like Otherside. Their narrative appeared robust and compelling until the crypto market cycle peaked and the broader market turned bearish. As the market shifted, the floor price for BAYC tanked, resulting in a corresponding decline in sentiment and attention.

Consequently, Igloo faces the daunting challenge of building crypto-native brands in a highly speculative space characterized by volatile attention spans and mindshare, along with participants who exhibit a strong bias for short-term gratification.

For more insight into the IP - check out Messaris The Story So Far: An Intelligent Approach to Intellectual Property and Azuki, Pudgy Penguins, and IP.

Closing Thoughts

The July 2024 fundraising landscape exhibited notable shifts, highlighted by a substantial 72.9% MoM increase in deal volume to $1.44 billion despite an 8.3% decrease in deal count to 177. This surge was primarily driven by three significant post-IPO projects within the Mining Operations and Support sub-sector, notably IREN, Alps Blockchain, and Argo Blockchain. Excluding these outliers, deal volume still increased by 8.8% to $908 million. The Infrastructure sector dominated fundraising, accounting for 52.67% of the total volume, with the Financial and Consumer sectors following, respectively. Despite varied performance across sectors, the overall market demonstrated a healthy MoM growth in deal volume.
